<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Swiftnotes on Coding With Matt</title><link>https://mdm508.github.io/swiftnote/</link><description>Recent content in Swiftnotes on Coding With Matt</description><generator>Hugo</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Tue, 29 Jul 2025 09:25:22 -0700</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://mdm508.github.io/swiftnote/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Functions</title><link>https://mdm508.github.io/swiftnote/functions/</link><pubDate>Tue, 29 Jul 2025 09:25:22 -0700</pubDate><guid>https://mdm508.github.io/swiftnote/functions/</guid><description>&lt;p>A function takes inputs and gives outputs. In Swift, we must tell the compiler the types of our inputs and the type of our output.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-swift" data-lang="swift">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">func&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#a6e22e">sayHello&lt;/span>(to name: String) -&amp;gt; String {
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">return&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#e6db74">&amp;#34;Hello, &lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#e6db74">\(&lt;/span>name&lt;span style="color:#e6db74">)&lt;/span>&lt;span style="color:#e6db74">!&amp;#34;&lt;/span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>}
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>sayHello(to: &lt;span style="color:#e6db74">&amp;#34;Mr.Whiskers&amp;#34;&lt;/span>)
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>sayHello(to: &lt;span style="color:#e6db74">&amp;#34;Tunses&amp;#34;&lt;/span>)
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>sayHello(to: &lt;span style="color:#e6db74">&amp;#34;Kitty&amp;#34;&lt;/span>)
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>&lt;code>sayHello&lt;/code> took a &lt;code>String&lt;/code> and returned a &lt;code>String&lt;/code>.&lt;/p>
&lt;div class="highlight">&lt;pre tabindex="0" style="color:#f8f8f2;background-color:#272822;-moz-tab-size:4;-o-tab-size:4;tab-size:4;">&lt;code class="language-swift" data-lang="swift">&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>&lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">func&lt;/span> &lt;span style="color:#a6e22e">addTwoNumbers&lt;/span>(&lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">_&lt;/span> a: Int, &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">_&lt;/span> b: Int) -&amp;gt; Int {
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span> &lt;span style="color:#66d9ef">return&lt;/span> a &lt;span style="color:#f92672">+&lt;/span> b
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>}
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;span style="display:flex;">&lt;span>addTwoNumbers(&lt;span style="color:#ae81ff">10&lt;/span>, &lt;span style="color:#ae81ff">20&lt;/span>)
&lt;/span>&lt;/span>&lt;/code>&lt;/pre>&lt;/div>&lt;p>If you add a &lt;code>_&lt;/code> before the parameter names you can exclude them when you call the function.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>